<seg id="13">The module & FSView; for & konqueror; provides a further view for objects with the MIME type inode / directory on local files. it can be used as an alternative for different symbol and text views to view the contents of your local file system.</seg>
<seg id="14">The special feature of & FSView is to map nested folder hierarchies by means of a so-called tree map. tree-Maps allow representation of the size of objects in nested structures. each object is represented by a rectangle, whose surface is proportional to its size. this size must have the property that the sum of the sizes of the subordinate objects of an object is smaller or equal to the size of the object.</seg>
<seg id="15">With & FSView, the size reflects the size of a file or folder where the size of a folder is defined as the sum of the size of the entries in it. thus, large files can be easily recognized even if they are far down in the folder hierarchy. consequently, & FSView can be seen as a graphical and interactive version of the & UNIX command.</seg>
<seg id="16">In & FSView, an entry in the Treemap display is a rectangle representing a file or folder in your filesystem. for easier navigation, the rectangles have meaningful color and labelling settings.</seg>
<seg id="17">The color of a rectangle, which is switched over View color mode, can display either depth for easy detection of the nesting depth or mapping of a different file property such as name, owner, group or MIME type.</seg>
<seg id="18">A rectangle can be labeled with the different properties of the corresponding file or folder. for each property, you can specify whether it will be displayed at all, only if there is enough space to display or whether the area of child rectangles should be used (and thus, you can specify the relative position of the caption in the rectangle).</seg>
<seg id="19">In the display algorithms for Treemaps, the rule should be observed that the area is proportional to the size of the entry. in the Treemap in & FSView, this target is not always complied with. frames are drawn to represent the nesting of the entries, and these frames require space, which is then no longer available to the subordinate entries. note that less space is lost for the frame if the rectangle is square.</seg>
<seg id="20">How to partition the space of an entry for the subordinate entries is left to the implementation. in this case, it is always advantageous for the labeling and avoidance of space losses through frames to create rectangles that are as square as possible. the best methods in this regard are rows, columns or recursive duplicates.</seg>
<seg id="21">You can specify the minimally shown area for an entry using the menu entry View. instead, a diamond pattern is drawn in the area of the parent item to indicate that this area is actually occupied by a child entry.</seg>
<seg id="22">Originally, & FSView; intended as a small test application and introduction to the use of the TreeMap widget developed for the use of Cachegra.</seg>
